   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28612_1817_04_03_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <salute>
               Sunday-
               My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>. B.</persName>-
            </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
                  I had an excellent letter<lb/>
               from your brother <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauW1">William</persName>,<lb/>
               which you will be sure, I <choice>
                  <orig>an-<lb/>
                  swered</orig>
                  <reg>answered</reg>
               </choice>, on the same day. -</p>
            <lb/>
            <p>I am glad, that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauW1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Beaufort</persName>
               <lb/>
               has written to the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StuaW1">Primate</persName>-<lb/>
               for various reasons, which I<lb/>
               will not detail. -</p>
            <lb/>
            <p>The manuscript which we<lb/>
               sent by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BlacX1">Major Blackhall</persName>-<lb/>
               has not yet been acknowledged<lb/>
               by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">Hunter</persName>.- <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BlacX1">Major Blackhall</persName>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28612_1817_04_03_page02.jpg"/>
                     
                     took it to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Holyhead_WLK">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Hollyhead</orig>
                     <reg>Holyhead</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName>, on the<lb/>
               20<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. &amp; had it I suppose<lb/>
               booked in the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Holyhead_WLK">Holyhead</placeName> coach</p>
            <lb/>
            <p>I request that you will have<lb/>
               the goodness to search in the<lb/>
               Office, for such an entry, &amp;<lb/>
               enquire as to the fate of the<lb/>
               parcel. -</p>
            <lb/>
            <p>Perhaps tomorrow's post, may<lb/>
               set us at ease on the subject<lb/>
               For <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">Hunter</persName> is a fellow who<lb/>
               would wait for a frank, tho'<lb/>
               he was ordered not to do so.- <lb/>
               Pray when you see him<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">insense</hi> him with the idea<lb/>
               that we think him very<lb/>
               unpunctual - <lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28612_1817_04_03_page03.jpg"/>
                     
                     From <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName>'s experiments<lb/>
               on pensile bridges, I am inclined<lb/>
               to believe that it will be, the<lb/>
               best plan, he can follow, at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Longford_IE">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Long-<lb/>
                  -ford</orig>
                     <reg>Longford</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName> - But as I am always<lb/>
               for proceeding par, <hi rend="underline">tatonnement</hi>
               <lb/>
               I am ready to assist him in<lb/>
               raising a bridge of 30 feet long,<lb/>
               upon the road under my wall &amp;<lb/>
               opposite to the chapel, raised<lb/>
               only 6 inches from the ground<lb/>
               over which, after previous trials<lb/>
               with great weights, of carts cattle<lb/>
               &amp;c - we will induce the Mail<lb/>
               Coach to drive frequently -<lb/>
               to accustom the horses &amp; the<lb/>
               coachman to the novelty.-</p>
            <lb/>
            <p>When you get to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName>
               <lb/>
               I beg, you will try to get<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28612_1817_04_03_page04.jpg"/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">R.L.E.</persName>
               <date>April 3 1817</date>
               <lb/>
               either my round or my flat<lb/>
               value, made water tight.-</p>
            <lb/>
            <p>I long to see your book, or to speak<lb/>
               with greater propriety I long to hear<lb/>
               of it. - If it should succeed, in any<lb/>
               high degree, it will certainly be, the<lb/>
               best patron, you ever had.-</p>
            <lb/>
            <closer>
            Yours<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">R.L.E.</persName>
               <lb/>
               <dateline>April 3, 1817</dateline>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
